        <hl1>What to Look For as Bush and Gore Debate</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Flint Jason Wainess letter on upcoming Presidential debates suggests that Gov George W Bush's and Vice Pres Al Gore's 'nonverbal language' might be the most important behavioral cue we hae regarding their character; recalls negative impression made by Richard M Nixon on television in 1960 debates</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lights, Camera . . .: It's Not Only What You Say, but How'' (Week in Review, Oct. 1):</p>
        <p>Don Hewitt, the creator of ''60 Minutes,'' who produced the first presidential debates 40 years ago,  bemoans the fact that the 1960 presidential debates put the emphasis on style over substance.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lights, Camera . . .: It's Not Only What You Say, but How'' (Week in Review, Oct. 1):</p>
        <p>Don Hewitt, the creator of ''60 Minutes,'' who produced the first presidential debates 40 years ago,  bemoans the fact that the 1960 presidential debates put the emphasis on style over substance.</p>
        <p>But if millions of Americans watching Richard M. Nixon on television thought that he looked sinister, we now know they weren't entirely wrong.</p>
        <p>In an era in which every word uttered by a candidate is parsed and subject to focus-group scrutiny, George W. Bush's and Al Gore's nonverbal language might be the most important behavioral cue we have.</p>
        <p>FLINT JASON WAINESS  Los Angeles, Oct. 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
